Cars4U Pricing Linear Model¶

Summary¶

Cars4U is tech start-up that is attempting to gain a foothold in the Indian used car market. The Indian used car market has recnetly grown as the demand for new cars has diminished. Generally speaking, new cars have more stable (less variable) prices across regions and dealerships than used cars. This is due in part, to the fact that new car prices are largely determined by the origninal equipment manufacturer (OEM).

As a result, Cars4U needs to be able to assess the price of used cars within the market. Develop a model which could enable Cars4U to better estimate the actual price of a used car to help them devise effective pricing strategies.

Objectives¶

  • Explore & visualize the dataset.
  • Build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars.

  • Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help Cars4U.

    ## Data Dictionary

  1. S.No.: Serial Number
  2. Name: Name of the car; includes brand and model
  3. Location: The location (cities) in which the car is being sold or is available
  4. Year: Manufacturing year of the car
  5. Kilometers_driven: Mileage in kilometers on teh vehicle
  6. Fuel_Type: Type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
  7. Transmission: Type of transmission (Automatic/Manual)
  8. Owner: Type of ownership
  9. Mileage: Standard mileage offered by the car company (kmpl or km/kg)
  10. Engine: Displacement volume of the engine in CC
  11. Power: The maximum power of the engine in bhp
  12. Seats: Number of seats in the car
  13. New_Price: Price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh = 100,000)
  14. Price: Price of used car in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh = 100,000)

Notes¶

  • S. No. is not actually a serial number. It's just a count that matches the index exactly. Need to drop.
  • On Name, this column will need to be split into Make and Model. Make may be a relavant parameter in the model as could certain models, but models will likely be unique identifiers. Will need to see once split.
  • Location, Fuel_Type, Transmission, and Owner_Type are all categorical variables with what appear to be clean strings.
  • Year is a clean integer. It can be changed to datetime format, but as long as years are the only information we need integers will work the same as datetime format for year on any given analysis.
    • Kilometers_Driven has no commas. Is already an integer, should work as is.
  • Mileage, Engine, and Power have units at the end of the number (kmpl, CC, bhp) which will need to removed and the columns made a float64 or int64. Mileage and Power should be floats, while Engine can be an integer. Data dictionary notes that Mileage is reported in kmpl and km/kg, fortunately these are the same units since 1 liter of water is 1 kg. Therefore, no conversion is needed.
  • New Price contains the currency units (Lakh), which will have to be removed. Lakh simply means 100,000, therefore, will need to place (10^5) in column name as reminder that values are that much greater.
  • There are many missing values. Mostly in New_Price and Price. However, there are also a numer in Seats, Power, Engine, and Mileage. Power and Engine have the same number of missing values, which makes sense as both are parameters of the engine of the vehicle. However, confirming that those missing values are from the same vehicles will need to be done.

"""Data cleaning and organization"""
# Remove Serial Number column
clean_df = raw_df.drop(['S.No.'], axis = 1)

# Split Name into Make and Model
"""First word is always the Make, all other words are related to Model""" 
df = clean_df['Name'].str.split(' ', 1, expand=True) # Split string into two differnt columns
clean_df['Make'] = df[0] # Create columns in dataframe of corresponding Make and Model information
clean_df['Model'] = df[1]

clean_df.drop('Name', axis=1, inplace=True) # Remove Name column from dataframe
del df # Delete temporary dataframe used

# Solve capitalization errors in categorical data
categorical = ['Location', 'Fuel_Type', 'Transmission', 'Owner_Type', 'Make']
for i in categorical:
    clean_df[i] = clean_df[i].str.title()
    clean_df[i] = clean_df[i].astype('category')

# Adjust columns with numerical data and units so unit is in column title and data is numerical
cols = ['Mileage', 'Engine', 'Power']
for i in cols:
    df = clean_df[i].str.split(' ', 1, expand=True) # Split string into two differnt columns
    value = df[0] # Pull values and place
    unit = df[1].mode() # Pull unit string
    new_name = i + "({})".format(str(unit[0])) # Format new column name to retain unit information
    
    # Replace orignal series with just values. Values are converted to numerical data
    clean_df[i] = pd.to_numeric(df[0], errors='coerce') # Only non-numerical is "null" so replaced with NaN
    clean_df.rename(columns={i:new_name}, inplace=True) # Rename column with the units included in the name

# Change New_Price and Price column names to reflect that prices are the value show x10^5
clean_df['New_Price'] = pd.to_numeric(clean_df['New_Price'].str.split(' ', 1, expand=True)[0], errors='ignore')
clean_df.rename(columns={"New_Price":"New_Price(x10^5)",
                         "Price":"Price(x10^5)"  
                        }, inplace=True)

clean_df['Model'] = clean_df['Model'].astype('category') # Turn Model into categorical data

Notes¶

  • Goal of the anlysis is Price, which has 1234 Nan rows. As this is the dependent variable upon which the model will be built all rows without that dependent variable will need to be dropped.
  • Mileage is missing because those are the only two Electric vehicles in the dataset and therefore do not have kmpl measure. Probably are approriately NaN. As they are the only two Electric vehicles, will drop and note that this analyisis excludes Electric vehicles. Note some rows for Mileage do have 0's, in which case those values will need to be interpolated.
  • Engine has 46 missing values. If Engine is missing Power, Seats, and New Price are also missing. Will need to check for relationships in non-values between those features. It may be possible to use the relationships to interpolate. For instance, using model and make to find the likely Engine should be a good predictor of Power. While Model again should help with seats and New Price.
  • Power has additional NaN values, which were input as null. Again interpolation of those values, likely based on Engine is likely a good route.
  • Seats has 6 values that have an Engine feature and sometimes a Power, but otherwise again match up with the same missing rows as Engine. Again may be able to interpolate infomrmation based on Make and Model.
  • New Price has thousands of NaN values. Will need to find some way to interpolate this. Perhaps based on simply appreciation of costs due to year, or finding similar Make and Models that do have a New Price.
  • Both Mileage and Seats have a minimum of 0 values, they are the only ones. These must be error values as a vehicle cannot have a 0 mileage or 0 seats.

"""Group data by model to match missing values on varous metrics to the same model vehicle which has reported that value"""
model_median = nan_df.groupby('Model').median() # find median for all numerical values based on car model

models = model_median.index.to_list()

seats = model_median["Seats"].to_list()
power = model_median["Power(bhp)"].to_list()
engine = model_median["Engine(CC)"].to_list()

seats_dict = {models[i]: seats[i] for i in range(len(models))}
power_dict = {models[i]: power[i] for i in range(len(models))}
engine_dict = {models[i]: engine[i] for i in range(len(models))}

Notes¶

  • Model contains not only what model, but freqently contains engine type (CC) as a decimal(float).
  • It also contains seat numbers as integegers. Attempting to extract these may help fill in NaNs within Engine and Seat

There are too many different types of Model to make it a useful categorical variable for a linear model. 2040 new columns once hot-coded will likely be too limiting on the power of the model in the end. Even the 31 additional columns based on the Make of the car will be difficult. However, removing Make and Model information completely would be haphazard. Will drop Model column in favor of the Make in preparation for a linear model.

That said, we can use both Make and Model to interpolate Engine and other variables that are specific to a type of vehicle.
